'''Washington Township''' is one of four [[Township (United States)|townships]] in [[Blackford County, Indiana]]. As of the [[United States Census, 2000|2000 census]], its population was 995.  County Commissioners named the township after [[George Washington]] in 1833, and it was part of [[Jay County, Indiana|Jay County]].  In 1838, Washington Township became part of the newly organized [[Blackford County, Indiana|Blackford County]].<ref>See <U+201C>A History of Blackford County, Indiana<U+2026><U+201D>, page 152.</ref>

==Geography==
Washington Township covers an area of {{convert|36.19|sqmi}}; {{convert|0.01|sqmi}} (0.03 percent) of this is water.

===Unincorporated towns===
* [[Roll, Indiana|Roll]]
* Silas (ghost town)

===Major highways===
* {{Jct|state=IN|SR|3}}
* {{Jct|state=IN|SR|18}}

===Cemeteries===
The township contains at least nine cemeteries: Balsley, Center, Hadden, Herbaugh, Leffler, Mills, Roll, Shields, and Schmidt.

